The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                               Business Briefs
                              
	 Mumbai, May 11: GMR Infrastructure, the flagship company of GMR Group, will raise up to Rs 5,000 crore through private placement of shares in domestic and international markets. The board has approved the raising of an amount not exceeding Rs 5,000 crore, either through preferential issue, or qualified institutional placement, or private placement of securities.                             
	 New Delhi/ London, May 11: The US buyout specialist Kohlberg Kravis Roberts has joined the race to acquire a minority stake in Vijay Mallya-promoted United Spirits Ltd, The Times has reported. The report said that Roberts faces competition from Diageo, the maker of Guinness stout and Gordons gin, for the stake in United Spirits.                             
	 Mumbai, May 11: Market regulator Sebi has made it mandatory for companies seeking the listing of corporate bonds and other debt instruments to maintain adequate security cover for them at all times.                             
	 Mumbai, May 11: Madhu Kannan has been appointed managing director and CEO of the Bombay Stock Exchange. Prior to his appointment at the BSE, Kannan was managing director with Bank of America-Merrill Lynch.                             
	 New Delhi, May 11: Software firm Microsoft will lay off about 55 employees in India, which is 1 per cent of its staff strength in the country, with the slowdown affecting its business and profitability.                             
	 New Delhi, May 11: Gujarat NRE Minerals Ltd, the Australian subsidiary of Gujarat NRE Coke, has secured a $50-million loan from a consortium of banks led by Axis Bank to support its mining operations in the country.                             
	 Mumbai, May 11: Lupin has settled the litigation surrounding the launch of the generic version of anti-depressant Effexor XR capsule, which is patented by Wyeth, in the US.                                                                                                                           
